This paper discusses the challenges of accommodating the demand for massive-scale IoT devices and high-speed cellular services in the physically limited spectrum without significantly increasing the operational and infrastructure costs. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper also proposes a new multi-operator network sharing framework that supports the coexistence of IoT and high-speed cellular services, which involves the use of information theory and communication theory, making it relevant to the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the security and privacy concerns associated with IoT devices, which falls under the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates the performance of the proposed framework using real base station location data, which involves the use of data structures and algorithms, making it relevant to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category.
